1 Brief description of animal model

Animal models have been widely used to investigate the impact of genetic and environmental factors on various phenotypic traits. To analyze the data obtained from such experiments, mixed-effects models are commonly employed. These models account for both fixed and random effects, with the phenotype values being a function of both.

While mixed-effects models have been used for several decades in various research fields, they have a specific significance when applied in genetics research. Random effects and their associated variance components play a crucial role in understanding the genetic factors contributing to a phenotype. However, these concepts can be complex and challenging to interpret. Therefore, it is essential to present them in a simple and easy-to-understand manner.

To illustrate this, let us consider a hypothetical experiment where we measure the response variable (phenotype) \(y_i\) on the \(i\)th individual. Some individuals have one or both parents unknown, while others belong to a group factor with two levels (1 or 2), as shown in the following database:

To capture the relationship between \(y_i\) and covariates, the most straightforward approach is to use a model:

\[\begin{align} \begin{array}{c} y_{ij} = b_{j} + a_{i} + e_{ij}, \\ b_{j} = m + Gr_{j}, \quad a_{i} \sim \mbox{N}\left(0, \sigma_{a}^{2}\right), \quad e_{ij} \sim \mbox{N}\left(0,\sigma^2_{e}\right). \end{array} \label{eq:basic_model} \end{align}\]

The model for analyzing the relationship between the phenotype values \(y_{ij}\) of individual \(i\) from group \(j\), can be represented as follows: \(b_{j}\) is the mean value for group \(j\), \(a_{i}\) is the additive genetic value of individual \(i\) (commonly referred to as breeding value), \(m\) is the overall mean, \(Gr_j\) is the effect of the \(j\)th group, and \(e_{ij}\) represents the experimental error term.

This model can be further expanded to account for more complex experiments. Using matrix notation, it can be generalized as:

\[\begin{eqnarray} \mathbf{y} & = & \mathbf{X}\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{Z}\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{e},\label{eq:animal_model} \end{eqnarray}\]

In the above model, the design matrices \(\mathbf{X}\) and \(\mathbf{Z}\) establish the link between the unknown parameters \(\mathbf{b}\) and predicted values at the population level \(\mathbf{a}\) with the phenotypic values \(\mathbf{y}\).

Under the standard assumption of phenotypes following a normal (Gaussian) distribution, \(\mathbf{e}|\sigma_{e}^{2} \sim \mbox{N}\left(\mathbf{0},\sigma_{e}^{2}\mathbf{I}\right)\), \(\mathbf{y}|\mathbf{a} \sim \mbox{N}\left(\mathbf{X}\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{Z}\mathbf{a}, \sigma_{e}^{2}\mathbf{\mathbf{I}}\right)\), and \(\mathbf{y} \sim \mbox{N}\left(\mathbf{X}\mathbf{b}, \mathbf{Z}\mathbf{G}\mathbf{Z}^{T}+\sigma_{e}^{2}\mathbf{\mathbf{I}}\right)\), where \(\mathbf{G}\) is the general variance-covariance matrix for \(\mathbf{a}\).

Assuming \(\mathbf{G} = \sigma_{a}^{2}\mathbf{A}\), where \(\mathbf{A}\) is a numerator relationship matrix (NRM) used to account for the additive genetic covariance between records of related animals and \(\sigma_{a}^{2}\) is the additive genetic variance, we get \(\mathbf{a}|\mathbf{A},\sigma_{a}^{2} \sim \mbox{N}\left(\mathbf{0},\mathbf{A}\sigma_{a}^{2}\right)\).

Additionally, we can decompose the matrix \(\mathbf{A}\) as \(\mathbf{T}\mathbf{W}\mathbf{T}^{T}\), where \(\mathbf{T}\) is a dense unit lower triangular matrix that describes the flow (trace) of genes in the pedigree, and \(\mathbf{W}\) is a diagonal matrix with values that depend on the knowledge of parents and parent inbreeding coefficients.

Before we begin the specification of this model in R, let us check how the design matrices \(\mathbf{X}\) and \(\mathbf{Z}\), and matrices \(\mathbf{A}\), \(\mathbf{T}\), and \(\mathbf{W}\) should be specified based on our example:

2 BUGS language and JAGS implementation

Users of BUGS do not need to be proficient in constructing full conditional distributions or choosing sampling algorithms. All that is required is to provide the model, data, and initial values, and the BUGS program does the rest. The key aspect that sets BUGS apart from other programs is the model description. The BUGS model language is described in publications by (Spiegelhalter et al. 2003, 2007). The two most important operators in this language are described below:

  • The operator ~ denotes the stochastic relationship between variables. For instance, a ~ dnorm(mu, tau) indicates that variable a follows a normal distribution with specified mean and variance.

  • The operator <- denotes the deterministic relationship between variables. For example, mu <- a + b implies that mu is the sum of two components.

  • Additionally, any text that follows the # character is considered a comment and is not evaluated by the BUGS or JAGS packages.

The animal model code presented here is a direct representation of the directed acyclic graph (DAG) using the BUGS language. The code shown below is similar to the one presented by Waldmann (2009a), but is more concise and generalizable.

# Animal model in BUGS language
AnimalModelBUGSVar <- function()
{
  ## Priors - precision parameters
  tau2e ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  tau2a ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  sigma2e <- pow(tau2e, -1)
  sigma2a <- pow(tau2a, -1)

  ## Additive genetic values
  for(k in 1:nI) {
    a[id[k]] ~ dnorm(pa[id[k]], Xtau2a[id[k]])
    pa[id[k]] <- 0.5 * (a[fid[k]] + a[mid[k]])
    Xtau2a[id[k]] <- winv[id[k]] * tau2a
  }
  a[nU] <- 0 # NULL (zero) holder

  ## Fixed Effects
  for(j in 1:nB) { b[j] ~ dnorm(0, 1.0E-6) }

  ## Phenotypes
  for(i in 1:nY) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau2e)
    mu[i] <- inprod(x[i, ], b[]) + a[idy[i]]
  }
}

Waldmanns’ proposal treats founders and non-founders separately, assumes that phenotypic data is available only for non-founders, neglects the inbreeding when calculating the coefficients of within-family segregation variance is not easy to extend. There are no such limitations in AnimalModelBUGSVar.

The length of variables may vary, but this can be accommodated using the list structure described in the JAGS manual. To use the AnimalModelBUGSVar package, users must provide pedigree information in the form of three integer identification vectors, namely id for individual identification, fid for father identification, and mid for mother identification. Additionally, a vector winv with the coefficients of within-family segregation variance is required. The length of these vectors is \(nI\times1\), where \(nI\) is the number of all individuals in the pedigree.

It is not necessary for the identifications to range between \(1\) and \(nI\), although this is commonly done. In fact, even character names can be used for identifications in JAGS. However, several other programs rely on the integer coding of pedigree members.

All unknown parents must be presented with the identification number \(nU\), commonly \(nU=nI+1\). This corresponds to an additional dummy node (a[nU]) in the DAG. The addition of a dummy node enables the use of the same code for founders and non-founders and is mandatory because BUGS/JAGS does not allow ‘zero indexing’ (e.g. a[0]) as has been suggested by Damgaard (2007a). Variables regarding the phenotypes are:

  • the number of phenotypic records (nY), individual identifications (idy) which link phenotypes and pedigree as sketched by \(\mathbf{Z}_{i,k}\) arc.
  • phenotypic values (y)
  • model predictor(s) (x), which can be either a factor or covariate, and
  • the number of fixed effects (nB).

When working with JAGS, it is not necessary to sort the data (phenotypes, pedigree, and identifications) in chronological or any other order. However, other programs that work with pedigree data may require the data to be ordered in a specific way.

Records with missing phenotypes are excluded, except for the pedigree part. However, JAGS offers a notable feature when it comes to missing values. If the phenotype is missing but other variables are not, such a record can be added to the data (setting the phenotype to NA), and JAGS will automatically impute a randomly generated value given the specified model. This feature can be used to create simulated data according to an animal model (e.g. Van Vleck (1994)).

To simulate data, it is recommended to use informative priors or preset values for some parameters to obtain moderate phenotypic values. If variances are assumed to be known, their values must be added to the data (Table 1.1), and their prior specifications in the model must be removed (see AnimalModelBUGSVar).

Since JAGS does not allow the specification of improper distributions, the developers suggest using a conditionally conjugate gamma distribution for \(\tau^{2}\) (tau2) with small values for both parameters, i.e., \(p\left(\tau^{2}\right)\sim Gamma\left(0.001,0.001\right)\). This is equivalent to \(p\left(\sigma^{2}\right)\sim Inverse-Gamma\left(0.001,0.001\right)\). Waldmann (2009a) used uniform priors for standard deviations (\(\sigma_{a}\) and \(\sigma_{e}\)) following the suggestion of Gelman (2006), who demonstrated that this prior appears to be less informative for models with a small number of groups (individuals) or a small between-group variance. However, this scenario should be of concern for quantitative geneticists analyzing traits with small genetic variability.

Variance priors in AnimalModelBUGSVar use a conditionally conjugate gamma distribution, enabling BUGS/JAGS to use Gibbs sampling instead of other, more time-consuming algorithms. However, this does not imply that the gamma prior for precisions should be preferred over the uniform prior for standard deviations. Users are encouraged to perform sensitivity analyses with different priors and decide whether priors affect their conclusions. Using the approach described here, JAGS users can easily conduct such analyses by changing a line or two in AnimalModelBUGSVar.

3 Animal models accounting or not for inbreeding

3.1 Example 2: Animal model ignoring inbreeding

# General JAGs definitions
#-----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Initialization
#-----------------------------------------------------------------------
initfunction <- function(chain) {
  nI <- 9
  nB <- 2
  nc <- 3
  stopifnot(chain %in% 1:nc)
  a <- b <- list()
  for(i in 1:nc){
    a[[i]] <- c(rnorm(nI,0,2),NA)
    b[[i]] <- rnorm(nB,100,10)
  }
  .RNG.name <- rep("base::Super-Duper", 3)[chain]
  .RNG.seed = seq(1,3,1)[chain]
  return(list(a = a[[chain]], b = b[[chain]], 
              .RNG.seed = .RNG.seed, .RNG.name = .RNG.name))
}

3.1.1 JAGs model

AnimalModelBUGS <- function()
{
  ## Additive genetic values
  for(k in 1:nI) {
    a[id[k]] ~ dnorm(pa[id[k]], Xtau2a[id[k]])
    pa[id[k]] <- 0.5 * (a[fid[k]] + a[mid[k]])
    Xtau2a[id[k]] <- winv[id[k]] * tau2a
  }
  a[nU] <- 0 # NULL (zero) holder

  ## Location priors
  for(j in 1:nB) { b[j] ~ dnorm(0, 1.0E-6) }

  ## Phenotypes
  for(i in 1:nY) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau2e)
    mu[i] <- inprod(x[i, ], b[]) + a[idy[i]]
  }
}

Some comments:

  • x[i, ] is the \(i\)th line of matrix \(\mathbf{X}\);
  • b[] is the vector of fixed effects;
  • a[id[k]] is the additive genetic (\(a_{i} \sim \mbox{N}\left(0, \sigma_{a}^{2}\right)\));
  • pa[id[k]] is the expected value based on parents additive genetic (\(1/2\left(a_{father(i)}+ a_{mother(i)}\right)\));
  • winv[id[k]] is the within family segregation variance coefficients;
  • tau2a is the precision parameter, which is the reciprocal of the genetic variance (\(\sigma^2_{a}=1/\tau^2_a\));
  • tau2e is the precision parameter for the experimental error;
## Writing the JAGS model
filename <- "model.txt"
writeJags(model = AnimalModelBUGS, filename = filename)
#-----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Jags
#-----------------------------------------------------------------------
## runJags
jags_params <- c("a", "b")
runJagsOut <- run.jags(method = "parallel",
                       model = filename,
                       monitor = jags_params,
                       data = tmp,
                       n.chains = nChains,
                       burnin = nBurninSteps,
                       sample = ceiling(nUseSteps/nChains),
                       thin = nThinSteps,
                       summarise = FALSE,
                       plots = FALSE,
                       inits = initfunction)

AnimalModelBUGS <- function()
{
  ## Additive genetic values
  for(k in 1:nI) {
    a[id[k]] ~ dnorm(pa[id[k]], Xtau2a[id[k]])
    pa[id[k]] <- 0.5 * (a[fid[k]] + a[mid[k]])
    Xtau2a[id[k]] <- winv[id[k]] * tau2a
  }
  a[nU] <- 0 # NULL (zero) holder

  ## Location priors
  for(j in 1:nB) { b[j] ~ dnorm(0, 1.0E-6) }

  ## Phenotypes
  for(i in 1:nY) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau2e)
    mu[i] <- inprod(x[i, ], b[]) + a[idy[i]]
  }
}

Mehrabani-Yeganeh, Gipson, and Schaeffer (2001) simulated populations and selected animals based on the computed additive genetic values, with and without accounting for inbreeding. They concluded that missing inbreeding did not affect animals’ ranking and, consequently, response to selection, even with high inbreeding levels. However, neglecting inbreeding results in underestimating additive genetic variance in the base population due to overestimated family segregation coefficients in non-base individuals.

Furthermore, when inbreeding is accounted for, the animal model, coupled with McMC methods, can infer the change of additive genetic variance over generations due to the Bulmer effect (Sorensen, Fernando, and Gianola 2001). However, the applicability of this method for evolutionary studies still needs to be assessed. Therefore, it is advisable to account for inbreeding if possible.

4 Cholesky decomposition of relationship matrix

Matrix \(\mathbf{A}\) can also be decomposed via the Cholesky method, \(\mathbf{A}=\mathbf{T}\mathbf{W}^{\frac{1}{2}}\mathbf{W}^{\frac{1}{2}}\mathbf{T}^{T}=\mathbf{L}\mathbf{L}^{T}\), which is useful for efficient numerical solutions as well as for Monte Carlo simulations. The diagonal values of \(\mathbf{W}\) are computed according to the following three formulas (4.1) which correspond to scenarios (from top to bottom): both parents known, one parent known (say mother), and both parents unknown:

\[\begin{align} \mathbf{W}_{i,i} & = & 1-\frac{1}{4}\left(1+F_{f\left(i\right)}\right)-\frac{1}{4}\left(1+F_{m\left(i\right)}\right)=\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{4}\left(F_{f\left(i\right)}+F_{m\left(i\right)}\right), \tag{4.1} \\ \mathbf{W}_{i,i} & = & 1-\frac{1}{4}\left(1+F_{m\left(i\right)}\right)=\frac{3}{4}-\frac{1}{4}F_{m\left(i\right)},\nonumber \\ \mathbf{W}_{i,i} & = & 1.\nonumber \end{align}\] In the case of ignoring inbreeding or no inbreeding, the formulas give values: \(\frac{1}{2}\), \(\frac{3}{4}\), and \(1\).

Waldmann (2009a) reported that his implementation is faster and results in Markov chains with better mixing (smaller autocorrelations) in comparison to Damgaard (2007a). The code proposed by Waldmann (2009a) first computes the parent average and precision (1 / variance) to sample from the normal distribution with these two parameters (see Variant 1).

## Transformed additive genetic values - variant 1
AnimalModelBUGSCholVar <- function()
{
  ## Variance priors
  tau2e ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  tau2a ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  sigma2e <- 1 / tau2e
  sigma2a <- 1 / tau2a

  ## Additive genetic values
  for(k in 1:nI) {
    u[k] ~ dnorm(0, tau2a)
    a[id[k]] <- u[k] * wsqr[id[k]] + 0.5 * (a[fid[k]] + a[mid[k]])
  }
  a[nU] <- 0 # NULL (zero) holder

  ## Location priors
  for(j in 1:nB) { b[j] ~ dnorm(0, 1.0E-6) }

  ## Phenotypes
  for(i in 1:nY) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau2e)
    mu[i] <- inprod(x[i, ], b[]) + a[idy[i]]
  }
}

Damgaard (2007a), on the other hand, first sampled from the standard normal distribution, scaled by the square root of a within-family segregation variance coefficient, added the parent average, and at the end scaled by the additive genetic standard deviation. The approach of Damgaard (2007a) is essentially the transformed ( independent) sampler for additive genetic values (e.g. (Waagepetersen, Ibáñez-Escriche, and Sorensen 2008; Shariati and Sorensen 2009a)). To highlight the differences between the proposed implementations, the code by Damgaard (2007a) was rewritten in two variants (see Variant 2) and compared for speed and mixing with the code presented here (see Variant 1). The original implementations of Damgaard (2007a) and Waldmann (2009a) were not tested because they are not generic.

## Transformed additive genetic values - variant 2
AnimalModelBUGSChol2 <- function()
{
  ## Variance priors
  tau2e ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  tau2a ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  sigma2e <- 1 / tau2e
  sigma2a <- 1 / tau2a
  sigmaa <- pow(tau2a, -2)

  ## Additive genetic values
  for(k in 1:nI) {
    u[k] ~ dnorm(0, 1)
    a[id[k]] <- u[k] * wsqr[id[k]] * sigmaa + 0.5 * (a[fid[k]] + a[mid[k]])
  }
  a[nU] <- 0 # NULL (zero) holder

  ## Location priors
  for(j in 1:nB) { b[j] ~ dnorm(0, 1.0E-6) }

  ## Phenotypes
  for(i in 1:nY) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau2e)
    mu[i] <- inprod(x[i, ], b[]) + a[idy[i]]
  }
}

5 Reording pedigree information

Generally, the internal ordering of the pedigree is often of little importance for end-users. However, it is essential to mention the function AnimalModelBUGSData assumes the pedigree is ordering so parents come before offspring (you can type ?animalModels::AnimalModelBUGSData in R for more details). The argument reorder from AnimalModelBUGSData function is logical, where setting reorder=TRUE causes a reordering of the pedigree (via orderPed() from the package MasterBayes) for the internal calculations, while the data is returned in the original order; if the pedigree is not ordered, inbreeding can not be TRUE because the \(\boldsymbol{A}\) matrix will bias the analysis.

5.1 Example 4: Reording pedigree information to evaluate inbreeding correctly

Here, we are inducing a wrong order in the pedigree and trying to come back into the original pedigree using the function orderPed().

6 Additional parameterizarions

Additionally, two other parameterizations of the animal model are interesting which involve the incorporation of NRM into the design matrix \(\mathbf{Z}\) to remove dependence between additive genetic values, e.g., \[\mathbf{u}|\sigma_{a}^{2}\sim N\left(\mathbf{0},\mathbf{I}\sigma_{a}^{2}\right).\] One approach is to use left Cholesky factor (Quaas, Anderson, and Gilmour 1984a) \[\mathbf{Z}^{*}=\mathbf{Z}\mathbf{L}=\mathbf{Z}\mathbf{T}\mathbf{W}^{\frac{1}{2}}\], where original \(\mathbf{a}\) can be computed using \(\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{T}\mathbf{W}^{\frac{1}{2}}\mathbf{u}\) or more efficiently with solving \[\mathbf{T}^{-1}\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{W}^{\frac{1}{2}}\mathbf{u}\] due to the sparseness of \(\mathbf{T}^{-1}\) (e.g. ). In a similar manner, Waldmann et al. (2008a) used a singular value decomposition (SVD) of NRM, i.e., \(\mathbf{A}=\mathbf{U}\mathbf{S}\mathbf{U}^{T}\), where \(\mathbf{U}\) is a dense orthonormal matrix \[\left(\mathbf{U}\mathbf{U}^{T}=\mathbf{I}\right)\] and \(\mathbf{S}\) is a diagonal matrix. Then the parameterization is \[\mathbf{Z}^{*}=\mathbf{Z}\mathbf{U}\mathbf{S}^{\frac{1}{2}}\] and \[\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{U}\mathbf{S}^{\frac{1}{2}}\mathbf{u}.\] JAGS implementation for such a parameterization can be see bellow:

AnimalModelBUGSZStarVar <- function()
{
  ## Variance priors
  tau2e ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  tau2a ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  sigma2e <- 1 / tau2e
  sigma2a <- 1 / tau2a

  ## Transformed additive genetic values
  for(k in 1:nI) { u[k] ~ dnorm(0, tau2a) }

  ## Location priors
  for(j in 1:nB) { b[j] ~ dnorm(0, 1.0E-6) }

  ## Phenotypes
  for(i in 1:nY) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau2e)
    mu[i] <-  inprod(x[i, ], b[]) + inprod(ZStar[i, ], u[])
  }
}

The reason for the simplicity of the algorithm is that it assumes that additive genetic values are independent and fitted with a homogenous variance (precision), while pedigree information is incorporated into the design matrix \(\mathbf{Z}^{*}\). However, this also implies that the entire dense matrix \(\mathbf{Z}^{*}\) of order \(nY\times nI\) must be passed to JAGS. Preliminary tests have shown that the CPU time is lengthy, making these two BUGS language approaches only practical for pedigrees with a small number of members. The same conclusion applies to the augmented parameterization of the mixed model proposed by Harville (1986a). Therefore, these approaches were not evaluated for speed and mixing.

AnimalModelBUGSZStar <- function()
{
  ## Transformed additive genetic values
  for(k in 1:nI) { u[k] ~ dnorm(0, tau2a) }

  ## Location priors
  for(j in 1:nB) { b[j] ~ dnorm(0, 1.0E-6) }

  ## Phenotypes
  for(i in 1:nY) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau2e)
    mu[i] <- inprod(x[i, ], b[]) + inprod(ZStar[i, ], u[])
  }
}

  initfunctionZstar <- function(chain) {
    nI <- 6
    nB <- 2
    nc <- 3
    stopifnot(chain %in% 1:nc)
    u <- b <- list()
    for(i in 1:nc){
      u[[i]] <- rnorm(nI,0,2)
      b[[i]] <- rnorm(nB,100,10)
    }
    .RNG.name <- rep("base::Super-Duper", 3)[chain]
    .RNG.seed = seq(1,3,1)[chain]
    return(list(u = u[[chain]], b = b[[chain]], 
                .RNG.seed = .RNG.seed, .RNG.name = .RNG.name))
  }

8 NIMBLE implementation

The NIMBLE implementation of the Animal model offers a powerful and flexible tool for quantitative geneticists. The code provided below demonstrates how to account for inbreeding and use Cholesky decomposition of NRM. This approach can be extended to other animal models, making it a versatile tool for various research questions.

One advantage of using NIMBLE is its ability to handle missing data, which is a common issue in many data sets. NIMBLE allows users to specify models with missing values, and it can impute them during the MCMC sampling process.

Another advantage of NIMBLE is its flexibility in specifying prior distributions. Users can choose from a wide range of prior distributions, including informative priors or non-informative priors, depending on the research question and available knowledge. This flexibility enables users to perform sensitivity analyses and assess the robustness of their conclusions.

Furthermore, NIMBLE provides a user-friendly interface for specifying models, data, and priors. This interface makes it easy for users to construct complex models without the need for specialized programming skills. Additionally, NIMBLE offers fast computation and efficient sampling algorithms, making it suitable for large data sets.

library(parallel)

# NIMBLE function
run_MCMC <- function(seed = sample(1:1e5, 1),  data) {
  library(nimble)
  sigma2a <- 1/3
  sigma2e <- 1
  nimble_params <- c("a", "b")
  nChains <- 3
  nBurninSteps <- 30000
  nThinSteps <- 15
  nUseSteps <- 60000
  #---------------------------------------------------------------------
  # Code
  #---------------------------------------------------------------------
  AnimalModelChol_Nimble <- nimbleCode({
  ## Variance priors
    ## Additive genetic values
    for(k in 1:nI) {
      u[k] ~ dnorm(0, tau2a)
      a[id[k]] <- u[k] * wsqr[id[k]] + 0.5 * (a[fid[k]] + a[mid[k]])
    }
    a[nU] <- 0 # NULL (zero) holder

    ## Fixed Effects
    for(j in 1:nB) { b[j] ~ dnorm(0, 1.0E-6) }

    ## Phenotypes
    for(i in 1:nY) {
      y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau2e)
      mu[i] <- inprod(x[i, 1:nB], b[1:nB]) + a[idy[i]]
    }
  })
  #---------------------------------------------------------------------
  # Model
  #---------------------------------------------------------------------
  myModel <- nimbleModel(
    code = AnimalModelChol_Nimble,
    constants = list(nI = data$nI,
                     nY = data$nY,
                     nU = data$nU,
                     nB = data$nB,
                     id = data$id,
                     idy = data$idy,
                     fid = data$fid,
                     mid = data$mid,
                     wsqr = data$wsqr,
                     tau2a = 1/sigma2a,
                     tau2e = 1/sigma2e
                     ),
    data = list(y = data$y,
                x = data$x),
    inits = list(u = rnorm(data$nI,0,2),
                 b = rnorm(data$nB, 0, 1))
  )
  #---------------------------------------------------------------------
  # Configuring model
  #---------------------------------------------------------------------
  compModel <- compileNimble(myModel)
  confModel <- configureMCMC(
    compModel,
    monitors = nimble_params
  )
  #---------------------------------------------------------------------
  # Building model
  #---------------------------------------------------------------------
  myMCMC <- buildMCMC(confModel)
  #---------------------------------------------------------------------
  # Compile MCMC
  #---------------------------------------------------------------------
  compMCMC <- compileNimble(myMCMC)
  #---------------------------------------------------------------------
  # Running MCMC
  #---------------------------------------------------------------------
  start_time <- Sys.time()
  results <- runMCMC(compMCMC,
                     nburnin = nBurninSteps,
                     niter = ceiling((nUseSteps/nChains) * nThinSteps),
                     thin = nThinSteps,
                     setSeed = seed,
                     samplesAsCodaMCMC = TRUE)
  end_time <- Sys.time()
  time <- difftime(end_time, start_time, units='secs')  
  return(list(results = results, time = time))
}

#=======================================================================
# Parallel computing
#=======================================================================
tmp <- AnimalModelBUGSData(ped=example,  Chol = TRUE, intercept = FALSE)
#-------------------------------------------------------------------
# Model
#-------------------------------------------------------------------
this_cluster <- makeCluster(3)
start_time2 <- Sys.time() 
chains_all <- parLapply(cl = this_cluster, X = 1:3, fun = run_MCMC, 
                    data = tmp)
end_time2 <- Sys.time()
timeNimble2 <- difftime(end_time2, start_time2, units='secs')  
stopCluster(this_cluster)
chains <- list(chains_all[[1]]$results,
               chains_all[[2]]$results,
               chains_all[[3]]$results)

timeNimble <- mean(c(chains_all[[1]]$time,
                     chains_all[[2]]$time,
                     chains_all[[3]]$time))

In our small example with only \(n=9\) individuals, JAGS takes 2.647 seconds to draw 60,000 samples, while NIMBLE takes 2.924 seconds to draw 54,000 samples using the same BUGS model. Based on this performance, JAGS may be preferred for analyzing small data sets, as it is faster due to not needing to compile the model as NIMBLE does. However, this conclusion may not extend to more complex data sets, as NIMBLE leverages a C++ compiler to optimize performance. Additionally, the choice of which package to use may also depend on other factors, such as ease of use and available features.

It is also important to note that the reported results may change if we significantly increase the number of samples drawn in the MCMC procedure. Therefore, it is recommended to carefully evaluate the performance of both JAGS and NIMBLE for the specific analysis and data set at hand, including running simulations to assess the sensitivity of the results to the choice of software package and other modeling assumptions.

9 The effective number of simulation draws based on JAGS program

We can compute an estimate of the effective number of independent simulation draws for any estimator of interest, denoted here as \(E(\mu|y) = \bar{\mu}\) (Gelman et al. 2014). Assuming that we have \(n\) simulation draws in the \(m\)-th MCMC chain, \(m = 1, 2, \ldots, M\), we would have a total of \(mn\) independent samples from the \(m\) MCMC chains if there is no autocorrelation. Therefore, an unbiased estimate of the posterior variance is \(Var(\bar{\mu}) = \frac{Var(\mu|y)}{nm}\). However, if there is autocorrelation present in the chain, we can use an estimator of the effective sample size (\(n_{eff}\)) defined as \[\widehat{n}_{eff} = \frac{mn}{1 + 2\sum_{t=1}^{T}\widehat{\rho}_{t}},\] where \(\widehat{\rho}t\) is the estimator of the correlation of the sequence \(\mu\) at lag \(t\), as described by Gelman et al. (2014). Ideally, we want \(\widehat{n}{eff}\) to be close to \(mn\) or at least a good approximation of it, which happens when \(\sum_{t=1}^{T}\widehat{\rho}_{t} \approx 0\).

Table 8.3 shows the estimate of the effective sample size ratio \(\widehat{R}_{eff} = \displaystyle\frac{\widehat{n}_{eff}}{mn}\), in which \(R_{eff} = 1\) represents the ideal situation.

10 Computing cost

Below are two variants of the animal model with transformed additive genetic values, proposed by Damgaard (2007b), which were rewritten and compared for speed and mixing with the proposed implementation in AnimalModelBUGSVar). The main difference between the two approaches is the method used to sample from the normal distribution with mean equal to the parent average and variance equal to the precision. In the first variant (Variantes 1), the normal distribution is obtained by transforming a standard normal distribution with the appropriate scaling factors. In the second variant (Variantes 2), a gamma distribution is used to sample the precision and the normal distribution is obtained by scaling a standard normal distribution with the square root of the precision and adding the parent average. However, both variants are based on the same idea of using transformed additive genetic values that are independent a priori.

It should be noted that the original implementations of Damgaard (2007b) and Waldmann (2009b) were not tested because they are not generic. Moreover, the proposed implementation in AnimalModelBUGSVar) is shown to be faster and has better mixing compared to Damgaard (2007b), according to the results of the comparison.

# Variant 1
AnimalModelBUGSVariant1Var <- function()
{
  ## Priors - precision parameters
  tau2e ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  tau2a ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  sigma2e <- pow(tau2e, -1)
  sigma2a <- pow(tau2a, -1)

  ## Transformed additive genetic values - variant 1
  for(k in 1:nI) {
    u[k] ~ dnorm(0, tau2a)
    a[id[k]] <- u[k] * wsqr[id[k]] + 
      0.5 * (a[fid[k]] + a[mid[k]])
    }
  a[nU] <- 0 # NULL (zero) holder

  ## Location priors
  for(j in 1:nB) {
    b[j] ~ dnorm(0, 1.0E-6)
  }

  ## Phenotypes
  for(i in 1:nY) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau2e)
    mu[i] <- inprod(x[i, ], b[]) + a[idy[i]]
  }
}

# Variant 2
AnimalModelBUGSVariant2Var <- function()
{
  ## Priors - precision parameters
  tau2e ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  tau2a ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  sigma2e <- pow(tau2e, -1)
  sigma2a <- pow(tau2a, -1)

  ## Transformed additive genetic values - variant 2
  sigmaa <- pow(tau2a, -2) 
  for(k in 1:nI) { 
    u[k] ~ dnorm(0, 1)
    a[id[k]] <- u[k] * wsqr[id[k]] * sigmaa + 
      0.5 * (a[fid[k]] + a[mid[k]])
    }
  a[nU] <- 0 # NULL (zero) holder

  ## Location priors
  for(j in 1:nB) {
    b[j] ~ dnorm(0, 1.0E-6)
  }

  ## Phenotypes
  for(i in 1:nY) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau2e)
    mu[i] <- inprod(x[i, ], b[]) + a[idy[i]]
  }
}

Additionally, two other parameterizations of the animal model are interesting which involve the incorporation of NRM into the design matrix \(\mathbf{Z}\) to remove a priori dependence between additive genetic values, e.g., \(\mathbf{u}|\sigma_{a}^{2}\sim N\left(\mathbf{0},\mathbf{I}\sigma_{a}^{2}\right)\). One approach is to use left Cholesky factor \(\mathbf{Z}^{*}=\mathbf{Z}\mathbf{L}=\mathbf{Z}\mathbf{T}\mathbf{W}^{\frac{1}{2}}\) (Quaas, Anderson, and Gilmour 1984b), where original \(\mathbf{a}\) can be computed using \(\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{T}\mathbf{W}^{\frac{1}{2}}\mathbf{u}\) or more efficiently with solving \(\mathbf{T}^{-1}\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{W}^{\frac{1}{2}}\mathbf{u}\) due to the sparseness of \(\mathbf{T}^{-1}\) (e.g. Waagepetersen, N., and Sorensen (2008)). In a similar manner, Waldmann et al. (2008b) used a singular value decomposition of NRM, i.e., \(\mathbf{A}=\mathbf{U}\mathbf{S}\mathbf{U}^{T}\), where \(\mathbf{U}\) is a dense orthonormal matrix \(\left(\mathbf{U}\mathbf{U}^{T}=\mathbf{I}\right)\) and \(\mathbf{S}\) is a diagonal matrix. Then the parameterization is \(\mathbf{Z}^{*}=\mathbf{Z}\mathbf{U}\mathbf{S}^{\frac{1}{2}}\) and \(\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{U}\mathbf{S}^{\frac{1}{2}}\mathbf{u}\). JAGS implementation for such a parameterization AnimalModelBUGSZStarVar) is straightforward because the additive genetic values become independent and fitted with a homogenous variance (precision), while the pedigree information is incorporated into the design matrix \(\mathbf{Z}^{*}\). However, this means that the whole dense matrix \(\mathbf{Z}^{*}\)of order \(nY\times nI\) must be passed to JAGS. Initial tests showed that the CPU time is so long that using these two JAGS approaches is applicable only for pedigrees with a handful of members. A similar conclusion also holds for the augmented parameterization of the mixed model by Harville (1986b). Therefore, these approaches were not tested for speed and mixing.

Consider now the code below, which shows an animal model with a reparameterized design matrix \(\mathbf{Z}\).

 1 ## Transformed additive genetic values
 2 for(k in 1:nI) { u[k] ~ dnorm(0, tau2a) }
 3
 4 ## Location priors
 5 for(j in 1:nB) { b[j] ~ dnorm(0, 1.0E-6) }
 6
 7 ## Phenotypes
 8 for(i in 1:nY) {
 9   y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau2e)
10   mu[i] <- inprod(x[i, ], b[]) + inprod(u[], ZStar[i, ])
11 }

The implemented functions AnimalModelBUGSVar, Variantes 1, and Variantes 2) were tested on a simple example described in section 1. The tests were performed using two approaches, one with assumed known variances and one with variances unknown in addition to other model parameters (\(\mathbf{b}\) and \(\mathbf{a}\)).

To evaluate the efficiency of the MCMC algorithms for generating accurate posterior samples in a Bayesian analysis, the sampling time reported by JAGS was collected, and an effective sample size (\(n_{eff}\)) was computed for each parameter using the CODA program Plummer et al. (2009). The effective sample size is almost always smaller than the sample size due to autocorrelations between subsequent samples in the Markov chain (e.g. Kass et al. (1998)). We are interested in the MCMC pace or computing cost per sample, which measures the average time needed to generate each effectively independent sample, to evaluate algorithm efficiency.

Therefore, the computing cost per \(N_{s}\) samples for the parameter \(p\) \(\left(c_{p}\right)\) was evaluated as \(c_p=N_{s} \times t_{n}/n_{eff}^{(p)}\), where \(t_{n}\) is the time spent for drawing \(n\) samples. Considering the model has \(P\) parameters, the average computing cost per sample was summarized as \(\bar{c}=\frac{N_{s} \times t_{n}}{P}\sum_{p=1}^{P}1/n_{eff}^{(p)}\), where \(n_{eff}^{(p)}\) is the \(n_{eff}\) for the \(p\)th parameter. However, often one or few parameters may have a worse mixing than the others and, consequently, limit the ability to decide which model should be chosen. For this reason, the maximum computing cost per \(N_{s}\) samples (\(c_{max} = \max\lbrace{c_{p}\rbrace}_{p=1}^{P}\)) was also considered, representing the longest time taken to generate each effectively independent sample.

All computations were performed on a Dell Inspiron 17 7000 with a 10\(^{\tiny \mbox{th}}\) Generation Intel\(\circledR\) Core\(^{\tiny\mbox{TM}}\) i7 processor, 1.80GHz \(\times\) four-processor speed, 16GB random access memory (RAM) plus 20GB of swap space, 64-bit integers, and the platform used is a Linux Mint 19.2 Cinnamon system version 5.2.2-050202-generic.

The original implementation by Damgaard ((Damgaard 2007b); variant 2 in function Variantes 2) is the most time-consuming approach, especially when variances are inferred. However, it should be noted that the implementation with the transformed additive genetic values (i.e., variant 1 in function Variantes 1)) consistently produced chains with a considerably larger effective sample size due to the a priori independence among additive genetic values.

To compare the efficiency of different implementations, we computed the computing cost per effective sample size using the method proposed by Waagepetersen, N., and Sorensen (2008) (Tables 10.1 and 10.2). When variances were assumed to be known, there was not much difference in cost between implementations, and the standard implementation was the best on average. This implementation was also the best when variances were unknown.

Shariati and Sorensen (2009b) conducted extensive tests of various MCMC samplers for the animal model and concluded that no single sampler was the best in all scenarios. However, they found that transformed and blocked samplers could be beneficial when there are large posterior correlations between the parameters.

10.2 Example 2

Let us now evaluate the performance of all model implementations using a more complex example with 5,000 to 10,000 animals. While the example is more complex, the underlying breeding scheme remains simple. We considered two approaches: one assuming known variances and the other assuming unknown variances along with other model parameters such as year and sex effects. We ran three chains with a chain length, burn-in, and thinning rate per chain of 5,000, 3,000, and 10, respectively.

10.2.1 Simulation procedure

We simulate a simple beef cattle scheme using the AlphaSimR (Gaynor, Gorjanc, and Hickey 2020) package and the work proposed by Lourenco et al. (2015) to set up initial parameter values. The simulated population has 1,000 animals (500 females and 500 males) per generation, where the generation \(F_0\) (founders) was generated using the function runMacs() to produce founder haplotypes. We also considered ten chromosomes, 1,000 QLT per chromosome, 5,000 SNPs per chromosome, and nine generations. The mean genetic value for birth weight (BiW) was set up to 40 kg, genetic variance equal to 20.25 kg\(^2\), and heritability of \(0.4\). Furthermore, we also established that males have 1 kilogram more than females on average.

#-----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Definitions
#-----------------------------------------------------------------------
nInd = 1000 # number of individuals
nQtl = 10^3 # number of QTL's / Chromosome
nSnp = 5*10^3 # number of SNPs / Chromosome
nChr = 10 # number of Chromosomes

# Number of Generations
ngen <- 9

# Founders parameters
meanG <- 40 # mean genetic value for the trait 
meanSexDiff <- 1 # mean difference between sexes

sigma2g <- 4.5^2 # genetic variance

# Heritability

# Error
sigma2e <- sigma2g*(1/h2 - 1)

#-----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Haplotypes
#-----------------------------------------------------------------------
founderPop <- runMacs(nInd = nInd,  nChr = nChr, segSites = nQtl + nSnp,
                     species = "CATTLE", ploidy = 2L)

SP$setSexes("yes_sys")
#-----------------------------------------------------------------------

Each year, we generate phenotype data, estimate breeding values, select \(10\%\) of the best males, mate them with all-female within a generation, and generate progeny, including their pedigree.

  Program ="Standard"
  cat("Evaluating", Program,": ", generation,"\n")
  year <- year + 1
  
  # Mate initial Sires and Dams

                         nCrosses = nDams, nProgeny = 2)
  
  # Select next generation based on genetic value
  # Males
  pop_males <- pop_start[pop_start@sex == "M"]
  
  # Females
  #SelFemales <- setPheno(SelFemales, h2 = h2)
  pop_females = pop_start[pop_start@sex == "F"]
  
  # Phenotype
  pop_males = setPheno(pop_males, varE = sigma2e)
  pop_males@pheno = pop_males@pheno + meanSexDiff
  
  pop_females = setPheno(pop_females, varE = sigma2e)
  
  # Dataset - trible
  RecSys <- RecSysMaleFemale(RecSys, pop_males)
  RecVar <- PullSumm(RecVar, pop_males)
  
  RecSys = RecSysMaleFemale(RecSys, pop_females)
  RecVar <- PullSumm(RecVar, pop_females)
  
  # pop_start
  pop_start@sex
  
  # Selection for the next mate
  SelMales <- selectInd(pop_males, nSires, use = "pheno", 
                          sex = "M")
  SelFemales <- pop_females

}

Figure 10.6: Mean and Maximum computing cost per sample (in seconds) for additive breeding values (\(a\)), fixed effect terms (\(b\)), additive variance (\(\sigma^2_a\)), and error term variance (\(\sigma_{e}^2\)) accounting for inbreeding and using Cholesky decompostion of the NRM (variant 2)

Here we demonstrate that using Cholesky decomposition as a prior can be an alternative to direct matrix inversion in solving a system of equations. However, it incurs an additional cost per effective sample, with a maximum cost per sample of approximately 82 seconds compared to the 12.5 seconds observed for direct matrix inversion. The computational cost of Cholesky decomposition grows as the matrix size increases due to its floating-point math operations per \([N \times N]\) matrix, which is typically estimated as \(\mbox{FLOPS}=4\frac{n^3}{3} = O(n^3)\) (Chari and Salon 2000). Nonetheless, this approach can gain the inverse matrix more numerically efficiently than from the whole matrix as we only need to invert \(\boldsymbol{L}\), not \(\boldsymbol{A}=\boldsymbol{L}\boldsymbol{L}^{T}\) (Alfriend et al. 2010). Cholesky decomposition is also helpful for efficient numerical solutions, and its computational rate and efficiency depend on implementation details and the computing device’s architecture details used to run the analysis (Chari and Salon 2000).

We observed that the animal model variant 2 using Cholesky decomposition of the NRM and Gibbs sampling algorithm has the highest mean and maximum cost per sample. Hence, we recommend avoiding this parameterization when running MCMC with a Gibbs sampling sampler. Our results showed the maximum cost per effective sample was 4400 seconds and 249 seconds for unknown and known variance components, respectively. Therefore, the original implementation of Damgaard ((Damgaard 2007b); Variantes 2) is the most time-consuming approach, and the implementation with the transformed additive genetic values consistently produced chains with considerably lower effective sample sizes when using the Gibbs sampling sampler. Additionally, Shariati and Sorensen (2009b) performed extensive tests of various MCMC samplers for animal models and concluded that none of the samplers was the best in all scenarios. However, transformed and blocked samplers could be advantageous when there are large posterior correlations between the parameters.

10.4 NIMBLE

To illustrate the cost per effective sample based on the NIMBLE package, we consider the animal model using Cholesky decomposition of the NRM and the Gibbs sampling algorithm. As shown in Figure 10.7, NIMBLE has a lower mean and maximum cost per sample compared to JAGS. Therefore, for more complex DAG models, we recommend using NIMBLE instead of JAGS. Additionally, the C++ compiler of NIMBLE does an excellent job of speeding up the analysis.
